# üìò Chapter 3 ‚Äî Finance & Accounting Security

---

## üß† Learning Objectives

By the end of this session, Finance & Accounts personnel will:
‚úÖ Understand cyber threats targeting financial systems and payments.
‚úÖ Identify fake invoices, phishing emails, and payment diversion scams.
‚úÖ Learn secure invoice verification and vendor validation methods.
‚úÖ Apply safe practices for online payments, reimbursements, and payroll transfers.
‚úÖ Know how to report and prevent Business Email Compromise (BEC).
‚úÖ Build a zero-trust, verification-first mindset for all financial transactions.

---

## üìö Slide / PDF Content ‚Äî In Depth

---

### **Slide 1 ‚Äî ‚ÄúCybercriminals Love Finance Teams‚Äù**

> ‚ÄúAttackers follow the money ‚Äî and Finance holds the key to it.‚Äù

Finance departments are the **#1 target** for Business Email Compromise (BEC) and invoice scams globally.

üí∞ **Why?**

* Direct access to money flows
* Access to vendor, salary, and bank accounts
* Regular communication with external vendors and clients

üß© **Example Case:**
In 2024, a manufacturing company lost ‚Çπ1.7 crore after accounts staff paid a fake invoice that looked 99% identical to a real vendor mail ‚Äî only the bank account number was changed.

üìä 83% of financial frauds start with a phishing email (FBI IC3 Report, 2024).

---

### **Slide 2 ‚Äî Common Threats Targeting Finance Teams**

| Threat                              | Description                                            | Example                                                                                                        |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| **Invoice Fraud**                   | Attackers send fake invoices using spoofed email IDs   | ‚Äú[payment@vend0r.com](mailto:payment@vend0r.com)‚Äù instead of ‚Äú[payment@vendor.com](mailto:payment@vendor.com)‚Äù |
| **Payment Diversion Scam**          | Vendor bank account details replaced by attacker‚Äôs     | ‚ÄúPlease update our bank details urgently‚Äù                                                                      |
| **Business Email Compromise (BEC)** | CEO/CFO spoof emails requesting urgent payment         | ‚ÄúTransfer ‚Çπ10L immediately for audit‚Äù                                                                          |
| **Phishing / Smishing**             | Fake links to payment portals                          | ‚ÄúClick to verify your account‚Äù                                                                                 |
| **Payroll Fraud**                   | Employee salary diverted to hacker-controlled accounts | Change request via fake HR email                                                                               |

üß© **Tip:** Always verify payment requests via a **second channel (phone or meeting)** before action.

---

### **Slide 3 ‚Äî How Invoice & Payment Fraud Happens**

1Ô∏è‚É£ Attacker compromises or spoofs a vendor‚Äôs email.
2Ô∏è‚É£ Sends a fake invoice or payment request with changed account details.
3Ô∏è‚É£ Uses ‚Äúurgent‚Äù tone: *‚ÄúPayment pending! Late fees apply!‚Äù*
4Ô∏è‚É£ Finance staff pays to wrong account ‚Üí money gone.

üí£ Once the payment is made, reversal is almost impossible.

üß© **Live Example:**

> Subject: *Urgent Invoice #4789 Due Today*
> ‚ÄúPlease process payment of ‚Çπ4,75,000 to new account number ‚Äî we‚Äôve migrated banks.‚Äù

---

### **Slide 4 ‚Äî How to Spot a Fake Invoice / Email**

| Red Flag                    | Description                            |
| --------------------------- | -------------------------------------- |
| ‚úâÔ∏è **Email mismatch**       | `@vend0r.com` instead of `@vendor.com` |
| üìÅ **Unusual file type**    | `.html`, `.exe`, `.zip` attachments    |
| üí∏ **Changed bank details** | New IFSC / Account Number              |
| ‚è∞ **Urgency pressure**      | ‚ÄúPay today or late fee applies!‚Äù       |
| üó£Ô∏è **Unverified sender**   | Not part of official vendor list       |
| üßæ **Inconsistent format**  | Old logo, grammar errors, wrong GST    |

üß© Activity: Show 2 real invoices ‚Äî one legitimate, one fake ‚Äî and ask participants to spot 5 red flags.

---

### **Slide 5 ‚Äî Business Email Compromise (BEC) Defense**

| Attack Type            | Example                                                                            | Defense                              |
| ---------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------ |
| **CEO Fraud**          | Fake mail from ‚ÄúCEO‚Äù demanding urgent transfer                                     | Verify via phone / Teams             |
| **Vendor Spoofing**    | Looks like ‚Äú[vendorname.invoices@gmail.com](mailto:vendorname.invoices@gmail.com)‚Äù | Use company directory to confirm     |
| **Mailbox Compromise** | Attacker reads past invoice chains                                                 | Enable MFA on all accounts           |
| **Payment Diversion**  | Bank details swapped silently                                                      | Confirm details before every payment |

üß© **Golden Rule:**

> ‚ÄúNo transaction without voice verification.‚Äù

---

### **Slide 6 ‚Äî Secure Payment & Accounting Practices**

‚úî Use **MFA (Multi-Factor Authentication)** on all finance portals (ERP, SAP, Tally, ZohoBooks).
‚úî Maintain **dual authorization** for all payments above ‚Çπ50,000.
‚úî Never process payments based on **email-only instructions**.
‚úî Verify vendor bank account changes with **phone confirmation** to official contacts.
‚úî Keep payroll and finance systems **isolated from internet browsing**.
‚úî Don‚Äôt reuse finance passwords on personal accounts.

---

### **Slide 7 ‚Äî Cloud, ERP & Email Security for Finance Teams**

| Area                  | Secure Practice                                  |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| **ERP Access**        | Use VPN or SSO; never login via public Wi-Fi.    |
| **Email Security**    | Use official domain, enable SPF/DKIM/DMARC.      |
| **Data Sharing**      | Use encrypted Excel / PDF with password.         |
| **Backup & Recovery** | Daily backup of financial data to secure drives. |
| **Remote Work**       | VPN mandatory, disable auto-forward in email.    |

---

### **Slide 8 ‚Äî Payroll & Salary Security**

| Risk                      | Example                                  | Defense                         |
| ------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Fake HR Email             | ‚ÄúChange employee salary account details‚Äù | Verify with HR directly         |
| Insider Theft             | Payroll admin copies employee PANs       | Access control & logging        |
| Salary Data Leak          | Spreadsheet shared externally            | Encrypt or use HRMS access only |
| Payroll Portal Compromise | Weak credentials                         | MFA + strong password policy    |

üß© Tip: Salary slips are confidential ‚Äî never send via Gmail or WhatsApp.

---

### **Slide 9 ‚Äî Finance Security Checklist**

# | Task | Status

--|------|--------
1 | Verify all vendor bank changes via phone | ‚òê
2 | Enable MFA on finance and ERP logins | ‚òê
3 | Never approve payment via email alone | ‚òê
4 | Keep finance PCs isolated from casual browsing | ‚òê
5 | Encrypt financial files before sharing | ‚òê
6 | Conduct monthly vendor data verification | ‚òê
7 | Review access logs of finance systems weekly | ‚òê
8 | Avoid using public Wi-Fi for online payments | ‚òê
9 | Use official invoice templates only | ‚òê
10 | Report suspicious payment requests immediately | ‚òê

---

### **Slide 10 ‚Äî Key Takeaways**

‚úÖ Finance teams are prime targets ‚Äî vigilance is your firewall.
‚úÖ Always **verify bank changes via a call or vendor portal**.
‚úÖ Never rush payments based on urgency or ‚ÄúCEO requests.‚Äù
‚úÖ Protect login credentials ‚Äî enable MFA everywhere.
‚úÖ Treat all invoices as *potential phishing attempts* until verified.
‚úÖ Build a ‚Äú4-eye rule‚Äù ‚Äî two people must approve every payment.

> ‚ÄúTrust your process, not your inbox.‚Äù üí∞

